Purpose
MOE‑01 is the primary robotic worker of the RAMA system. It performs all assembly, maintenance, inspection, and repair tasks in orbit. MOEs eliminate EVA risk, reduce human workload, and allow continuous 24/7 construction.

Physical Description
Shape: Flat octagon — literally the size and outline of a stop sign

Dimensions: ~2 meters across, ~1.5 meters tall

Chassis: Rugged, simple, repairable

Mobility:

4 motorized tethers mounted on alternating sides

Each tether can grab, pull, anchor, or tension against structure

Manipulation:

4 arm/grippers, also on alternating sides

Arms can clamp, hold, rotate, drive fasteners, or encircle cables

Power: External hot‑swap battery packs that MOEs can replace themselves

Sensors: Cameras, lights, heat sensors, motion sensors

The entire machine is designed to be simple, strong, and field‑serviceable, not delicate or exotic.

Control Mode
Early MOE‑01 units are 100% remote‑controlled from Earth.  
No autonomy required. No AI needed.
Three‑person control team:

Operator 1: Arms A + B

Operator 2: Arms C + D

Operator 3: All four motorized tethers

This keeps the system human‑directed, predictable, and safe during early RAMA construction.

Core Functions
Orbital assembly: Connect rim sections, tension cables, align geometry

Precision manipulation: Handles brackets, fasteners, cables, and structural elements

Inspection: Scans joints, stress points, and alignment tolerances

Maintenance: Replaces components, tightens connections, performs routine checks

Logistics: Moves tools, parts, and materials around the hub

Design Philosophy
Single chassis, multi‑role: One body, many tools

Tool‑agnostic: Uses standardized tool heads for every RAMA task

Self‑recovering: Can reorient and return to work after disturbances

Redundant: Multiple MOEs operate simultaneously; no single point of failure

Durable: Built for decades of orbital service with minimal replacement needs

Tooling System
MOE‑01 uses a universal tool interface that supports:

Cable tensioners

Bracket drivers

Alignment lasers

Structural clamps

Cutting and fastening tools

Sensor packages

Tools are stored in standardized racks mounted on the hub.

Operational Behavior
Works in coordinated swarms

Communicates with other MOEs for synchronized tasks

Uses the hub’s geometry as a reference frame

Can operate in shadow or full sunlight

Requires no human presence during assembly

Why This Matters
MOE‑01 makes RAMA:

Fast to assemble

Safe to maintain

Scalable without adding human labor

Capable of continuous improvement

Independent of EVA limitations

MOEs are the backbone of RAMA’s construction and long‑term viability.
